        The rest of the day is very quiet. After the messenger leaves, the plants disperse slowly—no one quite knows what to do with themselves; the answer they'd been building toward for weeks simply isn't an answer at all.

        I find Holloway in the maintenance room, organizing supply inventories—what they do when stressed: create order through categorization.

        I say, "Hey."

        Holloway says, "Kira."

        (They don't look up from the careful arrangement of nutrient compounds.)

        Holloway says, "I'm documenting our current reserves— we should establish better tracking systems to prevent shortage scenarios."

        I say to Holloway, "Holloway."

        Holloway says, "Perhaps a rotating stock methodology—first stored, first used—minimizes waste and ensures freshness."

        I say to Holloway, "You don't have to do this right now."

        (Their fruiting bodies droop slightly.)

        Holloway says quietly, "I don't know what else to do."

        I sit down next to them. (Scout has been following me all day—extra attentive, worried about everyone.)

        Holloway says, "The human resources manuals were supposed to help— they were our framework after after we failed the first human. Concrete guidance. We thought if we just followed the protocols, we wouldn't fail again" 

        ¶

        Holloway continues, "But they didn't work for you. Too rigid, too procedural—didn't account for actual needs."

        I suggest, "What about trusting what's already working?"

        Holloway finally looks at me. Holloway asks, "What do you mean?"

        I say, "I mean things are working—not perfectly, but far better than before. You ask what I need instead of scheduling automatic treatments—Remedy refines medicines based on my feedback—Runner waits for permission. We solve problems together without committees or waiting for approval." I gesture around. "This morning, before the messenger arrived, I was thinking about how good we've gotten at daily cooperation."

        Holloway says, "But that's just... making do. Improvising. Not systematic understanding."

        I say, "Is it though? Or have we actually learned a system through trial and error? We've built patterns, Holloway—actual functional patterns for how you help me and how I work with you."

        (Holloway is quiet—processing.)
      </text>
