        Remedy's form shifts slightly.

        Remedy says, "I suppose… yes — I have been developing better formulations through your feedback."

        I say, "Runner, you've learned boundaries — not by following a procedure, but by watching my reactions and adjusting."

        Runner's vines uncurl a bit.

        Runner says, "It's been… difficult — but yes, I'm learning what makes you uncomfortable versus what you welcome."

        I say, "And Holloway — you stopped just scheduling wellness checks and started asking what I actually need. That's huge."

        Holloway, sounding more confident now, says, "I adapted the framework — integrated care with procedure instead of replacing one with the other."

        I say, "*Exactly!*"

        I look around at all of them.

        I continue, "Every single one of you has been learning how to help me — not by waiting for someone to tell you how, but by paying attention and adapting. That's the answer we needed — the process of learning together."

        Scout bounces—agreement, excitement. They get it.

        Florence says, "But it's so uncertain — how do we know we're doing it correctly without external confirmation?"

        I say simply, "We know because it's working — I'm alive. I'm healthier than I was weeks ago. We cooperate better. That's confirmation, isn't it?"

        Velvet speaks up, surprising everyone.

        Velvet says, "Good outcome is authority too — a different kind."

        Everyone turns to look at Velvet. That might be the most philosophically complex thing Velvet has ever said.

        Remedy, speaking slowly, says, "Yes — Velvet's right. We've been seeking external authority to confirm we're helping correctly. But the confirmation is… you're surviving — thriving, even. That's validation of our learning."

        Runner realizes, "We don't need Elder Heartwood to tell us we're doing it right — we can see it's working."

        Holloway, connecting pieces, says, "The journey wasn't just transit to ask a question — the journey *WAS* learning cooperation. And the waiting period was learning adaptation. We were building the answer while thinking we were waiting for it."

        Florence is very quiet.

        Florence says, "I fabricated Elder Twist's wisdom because I wanted to provide helpful guidance — my own thoughts hidden behind authority. But maybe… maybe my own thoughts have value directly?"

        I say firmly, "Yes — your insights are good, Florence. You don't need Elder Twist's authority to make them valid."

        Florence's wheeled platform shifts.

        Florence says, "That's uncomfortable — but perhaps true."

        Runner says, "This whole thing is uncomfortable — we wanted Elder Heartwood to solve the problem, to tell us the framework. Instead we have to… trust ourselves?"

        I correct, "Trust each other — not just yourselves alone, but all of us together. What we're learning through cooperation."

        Holloway admits, "That's still terrifying — no procedures to fall back on, no authority to confirm we're right. Just our own messy learning."

        I agree, "Yeah — but also it's ours. Actually responsive to what we need, not trying to force reality into someone else's framework."
      </text>
