      <text>
        Scout bounces enthusiastically, then flows over to press against Holloway, then Runner, then back to me—connecting everyone, reminding us we're in this together.

        Remedy asks, "So what do we do now?"

        I say, "Same thing we've been doing—pay attention to what works, adapt what doesn't, keep learning together. We just stop waiting for someone else to tell us we're doing it right."

        Velvet repeats, "Keep learning together. Good plan."

        Florence corrects, "Simple plan."

        Remedy points out, "Simple doesn't mean wrong—sometimes the complex answer is that simple actually works."

        There is a shift in the room—not quite confidence yet, too much disappointment still lingering—but something like determination, or maybe just acceptance.

        We're on our own—no ancient wisdom coming to save us, no ultimate authority to provide the perfect framework. Just us, figuring it out together.

        That should be terrifying—and it is, a little.

        ¶

        But also? Maybe it's better this way.

        We've built something real through trial and error and paying attention to each other—not following someone else's procedures, but creating our own understanding.

        Holloway says, "Tomorrow we continue daily cooperation—track what works, adjust what doesn't, build on what we've learned."

        Runner adds, "And we trust that our experience is valid—we don't need external confirmation."

        I say, "We have each other for confirmation—*that's enough*."

        Scout bounces—agreement, confidence, optimism. Scout always bounces optimistically, but this feels earned. We've been through something hard together and we're coming out the other side.

        Later, after everyone disperses, Scout and I return to my room. Velvet has maintained the moss bed perfectly—still soft, still the right humidity. Runner stopped by earlier to check the environmental controls without being asked, and Remedy left a new muscle-recovery treatment with an adjusted formulation.

        Small acts of care, repeated daily—no grand wisdom required.

        I lie down on the moss, Scout curling up in their corner.

        We're on our own. But "on our own" means something different now—not alone—together; not abandoned by authority—freed from waiting for it.

        The answer wasn't in Elder Heartwood's ancient roots—it was here all along, growing between us.

        We just needed Elder Heartwood to fail so we could see it.
      </text>
